I’ll assess this as a classroom workflow, not just a technical build: safeguarding, practicality, bottlenecks, and a simple MVP architecture. I’ll also check the current OpenAI/Codex angle so the advice does not rely on outdated assumptions.

Thought for 5s
Yes — practical, but with one key change: do not make it feel like “children secretly using AI through you.” Frame it as pupil briefs → teacher/developer builds → class reviews output.

Verdict
Your idea is workable as a teacher-mediated vibe coding dashboard.

The strongest version is:

Child writes request → teacher reviews → teacher sends to Codex/AI → teacher approves/merges → child sees live GitHub Pages update.

Codex can work with GitHub repos, propose changes, and support PR/review workflows, so your “teacher as human gateway” model fits the tool well. 

Suggested structure
Each pupil channel should have:

Top static panel

Project title

“View my live page” button

“Latest teacher update”

Status: Waiting / In progress / Updated / Needs clearer instruction

Main one-way chat

Child submits requests

They cannot see other pupils’ channels

Teacher sees all channels in one admin dashboard

Teacher dashboard

10 pupil request streams

Copy prompt button

Mark as actioned

Add teacher response

Link to GitHub commit/deployment

Optional “merge note” explaining what changed

PIN protection
A 4-digit PIN is okay for a classroom prototype, but not proper security.

Use it only if:

no surnames

no sensitive data

no open internet discovery

channels are obscure URLs or behind a class login

teacher/admin area has real authentication

Better model:

/class/blue-panda
PIN: 4831
Not:

/class/dave-smith
PIN: 1234
Main practical issue
The bottleneck will be you.

Ten children sending vague prompts like “make it cooler” will quickly become unmanageable. You need structured prompts.

Use buttons or sentence starters:

I want to add...
I want to change...
The problem is...
The page should look more like...
The next feature should be...
Then the child fills in a box.

Best MVP build
For a first version, I would not over-engineer it.

Use:

Frontend: simple React/Tailwind page

Backend: Cloudflare Worker

Database: D1

Hosting: Cloudflare Pages

Student auth: channel slug + PIN

Teacher auth: proper password/login

Deployment: GitHub Pages or Cloudflare Pages per project

You could start with one shared repo and 10 folders:

/projects/pupil-01/
/projects/pupil-02/
...
/projects/pupil-10/
Each child’s “view my page” button links to their folder/site.

Classroom value
This could be very strong because pupils learn:

writing precise feature requests

debugging by describing problems

iterative design

version control concepts

testing changes

reviewing outcomes

computational thinking without direct AI access

That is arguably more age-appropriate than letting them freely use AI.

My recommendation
Build it as a “Pupil Dev Request Board”, not a chat app.

The chat metaphor is useful, but the educational purpose is better if each message becomes a structured development ticket.

Minimum viable version:

10 pupil channels
1 teacher dashboard
PIN access
request submission
teacher response/update
static live-project link
status labels
export/copy prompt button
I think this is genuinely usable in class, especially with a small group or coding club.


